    "b438: dimmed Gemini's brightness wash off all 1,321 in-game sprites using the pre-greening pool as the colour reference. After b437's green scrub was applied, the user spot-checked the pool through a custom mobile picker (new sprite_package/code/build_restore_picker.py) and noticed sprites still looked subtly lighter and washed-out vs orig -- not a halo, an across-the-body luma shift Gemini introduced during the round-trip. New sprite_package/code/restore_from_orig.py --mode dim handles it pixel-by-pixel: compute Rec.709 luma delta between current and orig, and where current is lighter by more than 15 (full effect by 75), blend its RGB toward orig with a smooth ramp. Alpha is preserved -- the Gemini-rendered silhouette and anti-aliased edges stay exactly as drawn, only the colour wash gets pulled back. Ran pool-wide in ~12s; tested clean against the stress patterns from b437 (slimes/cubes/venomscale stay green; dark-stone rooms unchanged; the user's 16 flagged sprites are idempotently stable). The dead band keeps real anti-aliased fringe untouched. Also new in this pass: --mode flood replaces a sprite outright with the orig flood-fill mask + RGB (used for one Gemini outright swap, P170 from pink round bottle to green Erlenmeyer flask -- the scrub couldn't reconcile mismatched silhouettes), and --mode trim keeps current RGB but uses the orig silhouette as alpha (kept for halo-only cases). Pool/version bumped; sprites look right.",
    "b437: scrubbed residual Gemini bg-green off all 1,321 in-game sprites using the pre-greening pool as ground truth. The b434/b435 edge despill was already running, but two patterns survived: enclosed interiors the key flood-fill couldn't reach (the see-through hole inside an archway, the panel of a barred door, the centre of a ring) sat there as solid bright-green islands, and edges that came back a hair greener than they used to be still carried a faint shift. Both are fixable from the orig pool: any pixel that's part of the sprite in orig should keep its ORIG colour (so a magic ring that drifted from cyan toward green snaps back to cyan, and an arch frame whose stone got greener returns to stone); any pixel that's background in orig but became opaque-green in the round-trip is by construction Gemini-painted bg and gets alpha cut. The 'is this orig sprite or orig bg' decision comes from a flood-fill of each orig PNG from its four corners with colour tolerance, robust to whatever bg tone that sprite was originally rendered against (green sheets vs dark-stone vs black). Two guards keep the cut from over-firing: a 1px dilation of the sprite mask forgives sub-pixel Gemini rescaling, and a cut only lands when the CURRENT pixel is actually green-excess (G - max(R,B) > 20), so dark sprite content -- stone walls, charcoal armour, dark monsters -- whose colour happens to match the orig's bg tone is left alone instead of being eaten. Whole pool: 4.4M px snapped back to orig colour, 85K px alpha-cut. Slimes, healing potions, gelatinous cubes, venomscale mail, the Vault Sentinel Dragon: still green, all preserved. Tool sprite_package/code/scrub_green_via_orig.py (uses /tmp/pool_orig.pkl as the reference) -- dev-only, pool is the artifact.",
